person.bio: Titus Schleyer, DMD, PhD, is an internationally known researcher in the field of dental informatics. He is currently Associate Professor and Director of the Center for Dental Informatics at the University of Pittsburgh. Since 1997, Titus Schleyer has been a recipient of a training grant for dental informatics from the National Institute of Dental and Craniofacial Research. Dr. Schleyer conducts research in dental computer applications funded by the National Institutes of Health, and publishes regularly on dental informatics topics in major journals.

personalStatements.statement: With the development of an NIH-funded collaboratory for disparities in oral cancer in 2001 (1), I began to investigate how information technology can support cooperative work among biomedical scientists. I extended this work in the NLM-funded Dental Informatics Online Community (DIOC) project, which is an open, worldwide community designed to connect individuals interested in dental informatics and stimulate collaborative projects (2). Since its launch in 2004, the DIOC, with currently over 1,000 members, has become the world's largest forum for dental informatics research. Findings from the DIOC project informed the design of the University of Pittsburgh's CTSA-funded Online Research Community which helps scientists find relevant people, information and tools within the University of Pittsburgh's biomedical research community. Its flagship project, Digital Vita (3), is a social networking and curriculum vitae management system which supports the formation of individual and team research collaborations. As part of this project, we investigated the collaborative and information needs of biomedical researchers (4, 5), designed a set of electronic services to meet those needs (3) and implemented a production system. Five months after its initial deployment, Digital Vita is in use by over 200 biomedical scientists at Pitt, includes over 3,800 publications, 620 grants and 610 presentations, and has received national acclaim. The project proposed in this application directly extends this preliminary work to leverage Digital Vita's social and expertise network for the active, targeted distribution of information.

Titus Schleyer, DMD, PhD, is an internationally known researcher in the field of dental informatics. He is currently Associate Professor and Director of the Center for Dental Informatics at the University of Pittsburgh, and co-director of the University of Pittsburgh's Department of Biomedical Informatics Training Program. Dr. Schleyer conducts research on clinical informatics applications funded by the National Institutes of Health, and publishes regularly on dental and medical informatics topics in major journals. In 2009, Dr. Schleyer was elected to the American College of Medical Informatics. In this proposal, Dr. Schleyer contributes important foundational work on the information content, structure and mapping of electronic health records. Early research on the information coverage of dentistry in major biomedical vocabularies evolved into work on NIDCR award 1R21DE018548-01 (PI: Schleyer), which is developing a pilot reference terminology for diagnoses and findings in general dentistry. A related study has investigated the information content of paper- and computer-based dental records. The study concluded that existing paper records exhibit limited agreement on what information dental records should contain and that electronic records only cover this information partially. In important follow-up work, Dr. Schleyer's research group is pursuing the development of richer, more comprehensive dental records through work on a standardized information model for general dentistry, currently covering approximately 1,000 data elements. This work is closely aligned with existing dental and medical informatics standards, such as the ASTM Continuity of Care Record Standard and the ANSI/ADA Specification 1000: Standard Clinical Architecture for the Structure and Content of an Electronic Health Record. Dr. Schleyer is currently working on mapping the data elements used by the NIDCR's Practice-based Research Networks to the information model for general dentistry, which will allow future extraction of research data from electronic health records. This approach will facilitate practice-based research by reducing clinician workload and secondary data entry, thereby increasing efficiency; making data available for real-time validation and integration into study data sets; and providing an impetus for designing research functions into electronic dental records.

I served as mentor for Dr. Thankam Thyvalikakath who is conducting research on improved interfaces for electronic dental records that provide cognitive support to clinicians during patient care and thus reduce errors. In this role, I have mentored her in developing research questions and methods, and in operationalizing the research protocol. As her primary mentor, I have also assisted her in the preparation and finalization of her research papers and a K08 grant application. My own research, very much in line with Dr. Thyvalikakath's, focuses on on improving computer systems to support clinical care. Our research center is currently evaluating practice management software, studying workflow in dental offices, designing electronic dental record systems that optimally support clinical decision-making, and developing advanced voice recognition and visual interfaces for clinical dentistry. As part of the University of Pittsburgh's Clinical and Translational Science Institute, I am focusing on developing systems to help researchers establish collaborations, and save time and effort in solving scientific problems. To date, I have served as mentor for over 11 predoctoral trainees and 2 postdoctoral trainees.
During the past year, Dr. Thyvalikakath has made excellent progress towards completing the KL2 project. Building on preliminary work process models developed through her cognitive task analysis study, she developed a novel prototype for interacting with clinical data during patient care. Currently, she is finalizing the protocol to perform a summative evaluation of the prototype. She is also working on writing papers based on it and also on defending her PhD proposal in May 2010. On June 17, 2009, she passed the PhD comprehensive exam and on August 1, 2009, she received a K08 career development award for a period of three years. As part of this project, she is currently working on conducting focus groups among dentists and dental hygienists to determine the barriers and facilitators for using risk assessment tools at the point of care. Her long term goal is to develop decision support tools that support the cognitive needs of clinicians at the point of care and thus assist in identifying high risk population for chronic oral diseases. To achieve this goal, Dr. Thyvalikakath has started collaborating on similar projects with researchers at other institutions such as Health Partners, Minnesota, and the University of Minnesota School of Dental Medicine.

With regard to clinical software applications in dentistry, I am currently focusing on three related areas; with Drs. Amit Acharya and Ovidiu Ciobanu, I am working on a comprehensive information model for general dentistry intended as a systematically structured blueprint for the information stored in patient records. A controlled vocabulary for dental findings and diagnoses, which I am developing with Dr. Humberto Torres-Urquidy, provides the content for the fields in the information model. A third research area addresses how these data should be represented to and entered by the dental team members. One main project in representation is a novel interface for displaying patient information that corresponds to the cognitive requirements of clinical decision making (work done in collaboration with Dr. Thankam Thyvalikakath). In addition, we are investigating to what degree three dimensional models can help general dentists make clinical decisions more efficiently and effectively. Our main project in data entry is the development of a natural language processing system for initial dental examinations. Another stream of research is focused on virtual communications, especially how to help researchers find collaborators and how to route useful information to them automatically. This work is applied in the Dental Informatics Online Community (http://www.dentalinformatics.org) and Pitt's Clinical and Translation Science Institute (http://di.dental.pitt.edu/orc/).

Titus Schleyer, DMD, PhD, is currently Associate Professor and Director of the Center for Dental Informatics at the University of Pittsburgh. He holds DMD degrees from the University of Frankfurt, Germany, and Temple University, Philadelphia, as well as a PhD degree in molecular biology from the University of Frankfurt and an MBA degree in Health Administration from Temple University. Dr. Schleyer has been active in dental informatics research since 1989, conducting seminal research on electronic dental records, and Internet applications, workflow and human-computer interaction in dentistry. Since 1997, Dr. Schleyer has been a recipient of a training grant for dental informatics from the National Institute of Dental and Craniofacial Research. Dr. Schleyer's research on dental computer applications is primarily funded by the National Institutes of Health. He publishes regularly on dental informatics topics in major journals. In 2009, Dr. Schleyer was elected to the American College of Medical Informatics.

In this proposal, I am building on several research studies that are foundational to the proposed project. Our research center was the first one to conduct a comprehensive study of the content of paper- and computer-based dental record formats (1). This study has provided us with an excellent understanding of what information the various formats, including that used by Dentrix, are designed to accommodate. In important follow-up work, we are pursuing the development of richer, more comprehensive dental records through work on a standardized information model for general dentistry (2). We are currently in the process of subjecting a list of 1,100 data elements drawn from previous research and de-identified patient records from general practitioners to categorization and prioritization through a formal Delphi process. Subsequently, the collection of data elements will undergo formal structuring into an information model. This model will provide a comprehensive blueprint for data collection in general dentistry. Last, we have assessed adoption and utilization of, opinions about, and attitudes toward clinical computing in the United States (3). In this study, we performed a basic analysis of the electronic management of clinical information by general dentists. Information categories such as appointments, treatment plans and completed treatment with a strong connection to office operations and billing were stored on the computer in the overwhelming majority of practices. The oral health status, intra-/extraoral images, diagnoses, radiographs, and the dental history followed in terms of frequency of computer-based storage. Medical history and progress notes, and the chief complaint tended to be stored on the computer least often. These research studies, combined with the fact that I have become intimately familiar with the operations of the three NIDCR-funded PBRNs as a member of the PBRN Monitoring Committee since its inception, position this research project optimally for success.

Since 1997, I have directed the (currently only) NIDCR/NLM-funded training program in dental informatics, first at Temple University and, since 2002, at the University of Pittsburgh. I have lectured on and taught a variety of dental informatics topics at the predoctoral, graduate and continuing education levels. I have participated in the establishment of the Dental Informatics Online Community, a virtual, global community for anyone interested in dental informatics. I have also developed several online courses, and conducted research on the design and development of educational software. Together with a colleague, I directed the development of the ANSI/ADA Standard "ANSI/ADA Specification No. 1001: Guidelines for the Design of Educational Software." I have worked and lectured with all faculty members of the Online Certificate Program team.

Titus Schleyer, DMD, PhD, Associate Professor and Director of the Center. Dr. Schleyer holds DMD degrees from the University of Frankfurt, Germany, and Temple University, Philadelphia, as well as a PhD degree in molecular biology from the University of Frankfurt and an MBA degree in Health Administration from Temple University. Active in dental informatics research since 1989, he has published one book and over 50 peer-reviewed articles in a variety of dental, informatics and computer science journals. Dr. Schleyer directs the concentration in dental informatics of the Biomedical Informatics Training Program offered by the Department of Biomedical Informatics, School of Medicine, University of Pittsburgh. The program has graduated numerous masters, PhD and postgraduate trainees, several of whom hold influential positions at research organizations in the US. The Dental Informatics Training Program has been supported by a grant from the National Institute of Dental and Craniofacial Research since 1997. Dr. Schleyer's core research interests focus on improving computer systems to support clinical care. Together with his collaborators and trainees, he is currently working on a comprehensive information model for general dentistry, designing a 3D-based electronic dental record, studying workflow in dental offices, and developing advanced voice recognition and visual interfaces. Dr. Schleyer was elected to the American College of Medical Informatics in 2009, making him only the fourth dentist to receive this honor since the founding of the College.

In this proposal, I contribute important foundational work on the information content, adoption and use of electronic dental records in dentistry. Early research on the information coverage of dentistry in major biomedical vocabularies (1) evolved into work on NIDCR award 1R21DE018548-01 (PI: Schleyer), which is developing a pilot reference terminology for diagnoses and findings in general dentistry (4). A related study (3) investigated the information content of paper- and computer-based dental records. The study concluded that existing paper records exhibit limited agreement on what information dental records should contain and that electronic records only cover this information partially. In important follow-up work, we are pursuing the development of richer, more comprehensive dental records through work on a standardized information model for general dentistry (5). We are currently subjecting a list of 1,100 data elements drawn from previous research and de-identified patient records from general practitioners to categorization and prioritization through a formal Delphi process. Subsequently, the collection of data elements will undergo formal structuring into an information model. This work is currently being supported through NIDCR award 1R21DE019683 (PI: Schleyer) "A Standard Information Model for General Dental Records." Last, we have assessed adoption and utilization of, opinions about, and attitudes toward clinical computing in the United States (2). As of 2006, approximately 25 % of all general dentists in the US had a computer at chairside but only 1.8% were completely paperless. The work proposed in this application represents an important initiative that will make future electronic dental records more useful for the type of interdisciplinary, outcomes-oriented research needed to improve patient care than they are today.

In this proposal, I contribute important foundational work on the application, adoption and use of technology and informatics interventions in clinical dental care (2). Our research center has conducted foundational research on the adoption of clinical computing (2) and the Internet (1). I also have published a matrix of technologies and the clinical tasks they can support, as well as how dental informatics research can help improve the quality of care. Insights the information needs of practitioners (5), and various detailed technology assessments, for instance of the usability of dental practice management systems (4)and the content of electronic patient records (3), position me well to contribute to the development of novel informatics interventions for evidence-based dental care in this project.

With the development of an NIH-funded collaboratory for disparities in oral cancer in 2001 (1), I began to investigate how information technology can support cooperative work among biomedical scientists. I extended this work in the NLM-funded Dental Informatics Online Community (DIOC) project, which is an open, worldwide community designed to connect individuals interested in dental informatics and stimulate collaborative projects (2). Since its launch in 2004, the DIOC, with currently over 1,000 members, has become the world's largest forum for dental informatics research. Findings from the DIOC project informed the design of the University of Pittsburgh's CTSA-funded Online Research Community which helps scientists find relevant people, information and tools within the University of Pittsburgh's biomedical research community. Its flagship project, Digital Vita (3), is a social networking and curriculum vitae management system which supports the formation of individual and team research collaborations. As part of this project, we investigated the collaborative and information needs of biomedical researchers (4, 5), designed a set of electronic services to meet those needs (3) and implemented a production system. Fourteen months after its initial deployment, Digital Vita is in use by almost 500 biomedical scientists at Pitt, includes over 14,300 publications, 2,000 grants and 4,700 presentations, and has received national acclaim. The project proposed in this application directly extends this preliminary work to leverage Digital Vita's document generation abilities for the VIVO platform. Importantly for this application, this biosketch was generated completely by Digital Vita.

In this proposal, I am contributing significant research on the utilization of and human computer interaction issues with clinical computer applications in general dentistry. In addition, I have worked with the research team on studying the feasibility and on developing a prototype for natural language processing in dentistry for several years. Our research center was the first one to conduct a comprehensive study of the adoption and utilization of, opinions about, and attitudes toward clinical computing in the United States. In this study, we found that 13% of the respondents used voice for clinical data entry. However, 16% had tried voice input and abandoned it, mainly because of problems with speech recognition, lower efficiency compared to other data entry methods, and incompatibilities. In a study of workflow during comprehensive oral examination and treatment planning appointments, we determined that clinical tasks and infection control requirements often made it difficult for clinicians to interact with the computer using keyboard and mouse, making voice an obvious alternative. In working on our NIDCR-funded project "Feasibility of a Natural Language Processing-based Dental Charting Application" (1R21DE018158-01), I have participated in developing a methodology for creating a semantic representation for information that will be automatically extracted from textual clinical records. In that project, we established an initial representation from a set of training documents and, iteratively evaluated and evolved the representation while developing annotation guidelines. The approach we developed is based on standard principles and approaches that are not dependent on any particular domain or type of semantic representation, and thus, highly generalizable.

personsFundings.description: Electronic dental records (EDR) for general dentists vary widely with regard to the content and structure of the information they contain. At a time when electronic patient records are becoming increasingly essential to delivering high-quality patient care, the "Tower of Babel" that today's EDRs represent is an increasingly significant drawback. Not only does this situation currently prevent computational approaches for supporting patient care (for instance through automatic, patient-specific retrieval of evidence-based dental resources), it also will significantly hamper the exchange of patient information within the emerging National Health Information Infrastructure. Our research indicates that incomplete and fragmented EDRs force many practitioners to maintain both paper-and computer-based patient records, which situation potentially contributes to the very limited adoption of completely electronic patient records by general dentists. The objective of this project is to develop a comprehensive, consensus-based Electronic Dental Record Information Model (EDRIM) as a reference standard for the content and structure of EDRs. In Specific Aim 1, we will iterative refine the previously compiled candidate list of data elements to develop a validated, prioritized, comprehensive list of data elements for documenting patient care in general dentistry through a Delphi approach and transform this refined list of data elements into a formal information model. In Specific Aim 2, we will conduct a formal evaluation study to asses the patient information coverage offered by the EDRIM developed in Specific Aim 1 by adopting a similar methodology used in the Large Scale Vocabulary Test conducted by National Library of Medicine and the Agency for Health Care Policy and Research. The goal of our project is to develop a consensus-based, comprehensive dental information model that covers at least 70-80% of the clinical concepts recorded by general dentists in daily practice. The proposed information model will have multiple benefits. First, EDR developers will have available a ready-made template for patient information that can easily be translated into a physical database design. Second, practitioners will benefit from EDRs that represent patient information more comprehensively than is currently the case. Third, future data exchange among dentists and their colleagues, as well as other members of the healthcare team, will be facilitated by a common data infrastructure. Last, rich and comprehensive EDRs will provide a significant opportunity to support clinical, epidemiological and health outcomes research. We expect the model to have far-reaching and beneficial impact on how patient information is represented and stored, how EDRs are designed and, ultimately, how electronic systems are used in support of clinical care and research.
